# Docker build-context excludes for the workspace image (deploy/workspace/Dockerfile).
#
# WHY THIS FILE IS LOAD-BEARING, NOT HOUSEKEEPING.
# The Dockerfile runs `RUN npm ci` against the committed lockfile and THEN `COPY mcp/ ./`. Without a
# .dockerignore, that COPY drags the developer's HOST `mcp/node_modules` into the image, overwriting the
# lockfile-resolved tree — and the runtime stage copies THAT forward. A locally linked, patched, or
# compromised package would ship to production while the Dockerfile comment still promised "npm ci
# against the committed lockfile", and the pinned lockfile would guarantee nothing. Excluding the host
# dependency tree (and host build output) is what makes the lockfile the real source of truth.
#
# It also keeps secrets and bulk out of the context that is uploaded to the daemon: .git, .env files,
# private keys, agent memory, and sibling worktrees must never enter an image build.

# Host dependency trees and build output — the image installs and builds these itself.
**/node_modules
**/dist

# Version control and local tooling metadata.
.git
.gitignore
.github
.agent_memory
.agents
.superpowers
.claude
.worktrees

# Secrets and credentials — never in a build context.
**/.env
**/.env.*
**/*.pem
**/*.key

# Editor/OS noise and logs.
**/*.log
**/.DS_Store
**/coverage
